leased by Blizzard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wiki.gamedetectives.net/index.php?title=Sombra_ARG|title=Sombra ARG - Game Detectives Wiki|website=wiki.gamedetectives.net|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n| Puzzle solving by online communities.\n|\n| Complete\n|-\n| ''[[Hello Neighbor]]''\n| 2017\n| [[tinyBuild]], DynamicPixels\n| Unknown\n| Clues in the Alpha releases of Hello Neighbor are leading to the announcement of a new release. Incomplete.\n| Puzzle solving, horror, adventure and general entertainment.\n|\n| Ongoing\n|-\n| [[Waking Titan (ARG)|''Waking Titan'']]\n| 2017\n| [[Hello Games]]\n| ''[[No Man's Sky]]''\n|\n| Puzzle solving.\n|\n| Complete\n|-\n| [[Twenty One Pilots#2018\u2013present: Trench|''DEMA'']]\n| 2018\n| [[Twenty One Pilots]]\n| [[Trench (album)|''Trench'']]\n| The story of a man named Clancy, escaping from an oppressive organization called DEMA.\n| It included a cryptic series of websites (all hosted by dmaorg.info) with images, letters from the main character, and codes to decipher. It was discussed and solved in both a [[Reddit]] megathread<ref>{{cite web|url=https://old.reddit.com/r/twentyonepilots/comments/8dyoqk/twenty_one_pilots_2018_return_megathread/|title=Twenty One Pilots 2018 Return [MEGATHREAD]|access-date=2019-01-05}}</ref> and a Discord server. The ARG ended when Twenty One Pilots announced the end of their hiatus and released two songs from the album ''Trench'', \"Jumpsuit\" and \"Nico and the Niners\" (both of which contain themes and characters from the ARG).\n| 2,000+ Twenty One Pilots fans\n| Complete\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Video game lists by genre}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Alternate Reality Games}}\n[[Category:Alternate reality games|*]]\n[[Category:Video game lists by genre|alternate reality games]]\n", "name_user": "Phuzion", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed formatting, add wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_alternate_reality_games"}
{"title_page": "Sayed Morad Khan", "text_new": "{{Infobox monarch\n| name               = Sayed Morad Khan\n| title              = \n| image              = Sayed Murad Zand.png\n| caption            = \n| succession         = [[List of kings of Persia|Shah of Iran]]\n| reign              = 1789-1789\n| birth_date         = ?\n| death_date         = 1789\n| death_place        = [[Shiraz]]\n| burial_date        = \n| burial_place       =\n| predecessor        = [[Jafar Khan]]\n| successor          = [[Lotf Ali Khan]]\n| royal house        = \n| dynasty            = [[Zand dynasty]]\n| father             = [[Ali-Morad Khan Zand]]\n| mother             = \n| issue              =\n| religion           = [[Twelver|Twelver Shia Islam]]\n}}\n\n'''Sayed Morad Khan''', was a ''[[Shah]]'' of [[Iran]] who reigned from January 23, 1789 until May 10, 1789. He was the eighth king of the [[Zand dynasty]]. His brief reign is indicative of the ruthless and brutal struggle for power that prevailed among members of the Zand family following the death of [[Karim Khan Zand]] in 1779.\n[[File:Ali Murad Khan zand court.png|thumb|201x201px|left|King [[Ali-Morad Khan Zand]] (centre), at his court beside an unnamed Princess (left) and his son: Prince '''Sayed Morad Khan''' (right)]]\n\n==Life==\nSayed Murad Khan was a member of the court of his predecessor, Jafar Khan, in the Zand capital of Shiraz.  It was apparently Jafar Khan's treatment  of Sayed Murad Khan that led the latter to plot the king's overthrow. Sayed Murad Khan had been governor of Shiraz but was later confined with his family and, according to one account beaten on Jafar Khan's orders in an effort to force him to divulge his wealth.<ref name=\"Malcolm\">Malcolm, John, ''The History of Persia, Vol. II, Part 1'',1829 footnote, p. 106.</ref>\n\nIn 1789 a group of individuals, led by Sayed Murad Khan conspired to poison Jafar Khan. A female slave was employed to carry out their wishes. Sayed Murad Khan and his followers overcame the weakened shah, killing him and throwing his head from the citadel.\n\nAfter the murder of [[Jafar Khan]], Sayed Murad became the king of Iran.  Jafar Khan's son, [[Lotf Ali Khan]], then marched to Shiraz, where he was popular among the people.  Sayed Murad Khan held out for a short while in the city's citadel, but after reigning for less than 4 months he was forced to surrender and was executed.  [[Lotf Ali Khan]] succeeded him on  May 10, 1789.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Perry, John R., ''Karim Khan Zand A History of Iran 1747-1779'', {{ISBN|0-226-66098-2}}, Univ. of Chicago Press, 1979, pg. 299 \n*Waring, Edward Scott, \"A Tour to Sheeraz by the Route of Kazroon and Feerozabad\", {{ISBN|1-4021-4338-9}}, Elibron Classics, 2005.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rulers.org/ruli.html Rulers of Iran]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Zand Dynasty]]||?||1789}}\n{{s-roy|ir|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jafar Khan|Jafar Khan Zand]]  }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Persian Shahs|Shah of Persia]]  |years=1789}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lotf Ali Khan|Lotf Ali Khan Zand]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Zand Rulers}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sayed Murad Khan}}\n[[Category:Zand monarchs]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Murdered Persian monarchs]]\n[[Category:1789 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Iranian people]]\n[[Category:18th-century murdered monarchs]]\n\n\n{{Iran-royal-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox monarch\n| name               = Sayed Morad Khan\n| title              = \n| image              = Sayed Murad Zand.png\n| caption            = \n| succession         = [[List of kings of Persia|Shah of Iran]]\n| reign              = 1789-1789\n| birth_date         = ?\n| death_date         = 1789\n| death_place        = [[Shiraz]]\n| burial_date        = \n| burial_place       =\n| predecessor        = [[Jafar Khan]]\n| successor          = [[Lotf Ali Khan]]\n| royal house        = \n| dynasty            = [[Zand dynasty]]\n| father             = [[Ali-Morad Khan Zand]]\n| mother             = \n| issue              =\n| religion           = [[Twelver|Twelver Shia Islam]]\n}}\n\n'''Sayed Morad Khan''', was a ''[[Shah]]'' of [[Iran]] who reigned from January 23, 1789 until May 10, 1789. He was the eighth king of the [[Zand dynasty]]. His brief reign is indicative of the ruthless and brutal struggle for power that prevailed among members of the Zand family following the death of Karim Khan Zand in 1779.\n[[File:Ali Murad Khan zand court.png|thumb|201x201px|left|King [[Ali-Morad Khan Zand]] (centre), at his court beside an unnamed Princess (left) and his son: Prince '''Sayed Morad Khan''' (right)]]\n\n==Life==\nSayed Murad Khan was a member of the court of his predecessor, Jafar Khan, in the Zand capital of Shiraz.  It was apparently Jafar Khan's treatment  of Sayed Murad Khan that led the latter to plot the king's overthrow. Sayed Murad Khan had been governor of Shiraz but was later confined with his family and, according to one account beaten on Jafar Khan's orders in an effort to force him to divulge his wealth.<ref name=\"Malcolm\">Malcolm, John, ''The History of Persia, Vol. II, Part 1'',1829 footnote, p. 106.</ref>\n\nIn 1789 a group of individuals, led by Sayed Murad Khan conspired to poison Jafar Khan. A female slave was employed to carry out their wishes. Sayed Murad Khan and his followers overcame the weakened shah, killing him and throwing his head from the citadel.\n\nAfter the murder of [[Jafar Khan]], Sayed Murad became the king of Iran.  Jafar Khan's son, [[Lotf Ali Khan]], then marched to Shiraz, where he was popular among the people.  Sayed Murad Khan held out for a short while in the city's citadel, but after reigning for less than 4 months he was forced to surrender and was executed.  Lotf Ali Khan succeeded him on  May 10, 1789.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Perry, John R., ''Karim Khan Zand A History of Iran 1747-1779'', {{ISBN|0-226-66098-2}}, Univ. of Chicago Press, 1979, pg. 299 \n*Waring, Edward Scott, \"A Tour to Sheeraz by the Route of Kazroon and Feerozabad\", {{ISBN|1-4021-4338-9}}, Elibron Classics, 2005.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rulers.org/ruli.html Rulers of Iran]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Zand Dynasty]]||?||1789}}\n{{s-roy|ir|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jafar Khan|Jafar Khan Zand]]  }}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Persian Shahs|Shah of Persia]]  |years=1789}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lotf Ali Khan|Lotf Ali Khan Zand]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Zand Rulers}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sayed Murad Khan}}\n[[Category:Zand monarchs]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Murdered Persian monarchs]]\n[[Category:1789 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Iranian people]]\n[[Category:18th-century murdered monarchs]]\n\n\n{{Iran-royal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mpj7", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding/removing wikilink(s)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sayed_Morad_Khan"}
{"title_page": "French cruiser Lavoisier", "text_new": "{{other ships|French ship Lavoisier}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=''Lavoisier''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Lavoisier-Bougault.jpg\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|France|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Lavoisier''\n|Ship namesake=[[Antoine Lavoisier]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=1893\n|Ship launched=17 April 1896\n|Ship completed=1897\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=December 1897\n|Ship out of service=14 December 1917\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck= 7 June 1920\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Sold for scrap\n|Ship status=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Linois|cruiser}}\n|Ship displacement=2300 tonnes      \n|Ship length={{convert|100.6|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|10.7|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{convert|5.5|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship power={{convert|7400|shp|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=2 Indret steam engines, 16 boilers\n|Ship speed={{convert|20|kn}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=250\n|Ship armament=*4 \u00d7 [[Canon de 138 mm Mod\u00e8le 1893 naval gun|{{convert|138.6|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}]]/45 guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[Canon de 100 mm Mod\u00e8le 1891|{{convert|100|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}]]/45 guns\n*8 \u00d7 [[QF 3-pounder Hotchkiss|{{convert|47|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}]]/40 guns\n*2 [[torpedo tube]]s\n|Ship armour=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Lavoisier''''' was a [[protected cruiser]] of the [[French Navy]], named in honour of [[Antoine Lavoisier]].\n\nLaunched in Rochefort in April 1896, ''Lavoisier'' entered service in December 1897. She was then sent to [[Toulon]] as a replacement for the ageing {{ship|French cruiser|Cosmao||2}}.\n\nIn 1903, she replaced the cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|Isly||2}} as division chief at the station of Newfoundland.\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], ''Lavoisier'' patrolled the Atlantic and the English Channel, before being sent in Eastern Mediterranean in 1915.\n\nIn 1919, she was appointed to the station of Syria.\n\nShe was struck in 1920, and sold for scrap the next year.\n\n\n==Design==\n{{main|Linois-class cruiser}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n  | editor1-last = Gardiner\n  | editor1-first = Robert\n  | year = 1979\n  | title = Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1860\u20131905\n  | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-85177-133-5\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Gardiner}}\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/conwaysallworlds0000unse_l2e2\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  |editor1-last=Gardiner\n  |editor1-first=Robert\n  |editor2-last=Gray\n  |editor2-first=Randal\n  |title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships: 1906\u20131921\n  |year=1985\n  |location=Annapolis\n  |publisher=Naval Institute Press\n  |isbn=0-87021-907-3\n  |lastauthoramp=y\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Gardiner & Gray}}\n  }}\n* {{cite journal\n  |last=Meirat\n  |first=Jean\n  |year=1975\n  |title=Details and Operational History of the Third-Class Cruiser Lavoisier\n  |journal=F. P. D. S. Newsletter\n  |publisher=F. P. D. S.\n  |location=Akron\n  |volume=III\n  |issue=3\n  |pages=20\u201323\n  |oclc=41554533\n  |ref={{sfnref|Meirat}}\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ropp|authorlink=Theodore Ropp\n  | first = Theodore\n  | title = The Development of a Modern Navy: French Naval Policy, 1871\u20131904\n  | editor-last = Roberts\n  | editor-first = Stephen S.\n  | year = 1987\n  | location = Annapolis\n  | publisher = Naval Institute Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-87021-141-6\n  |ref={{sfnRef|Ropp}}\n  }}\n\n{{Linois-class cruiser}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lavoisier}}\n[[Category:Linois-class cruisers]]\n[[Category:Ships built in France]]\n[[Category:1896 ships]]\n[[Category:World War I cruisers of France]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|French ship Lavoisier}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=''Lavoisier''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Lavoisier-Bougault.jpg\n|Ship caption=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|France|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Lavoisier''\n|Ship namesake=[[Antoine Lavoisier]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship laid down=1893\n|Ship launched=17 April 1896\n|Ship completed=1897\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=December 1897\n|Ship out of service=14 December 1917\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck= 7 June 1920\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=Sold for scrap\n|Ship status=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Linois|cruiser}}\n|Ship displacement=2300 tonnes      \n|Ship length={{convert|100.6|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|10.7|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{convert|5.5|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship power={{convert|7400|shp|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=2 Indret steam engines, 16 boilers\n|Ship speed={{convert|20|kn}}\n|Ship range=\n|Ship complement=250\n|Ship armament=*4 \u00d7 [[Canon de 138 mm Mod\u00e8le 1893 naval gun|{{convert|138.6|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}]]/45 guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[Canon de 100 mm Mod\u00e8le 1891|{{convert|100|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}]]/45 guns\n*8 \u00d7 [[QF 3-pounder Hotchkiss|{{convert|47|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}]]/40 guns\n*2 [[torpedo tube]]s\n|Ship armour=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Lavoisier''''' was a [[protected cruiser]] of the [[French Navy]], named in honour of [[Antoine Lavoisier]].\n\nLaunched in Rochefort in April 1896, ''Lavoisier'' entered service in December 1897. She was then sent to [[Toulon]] as a replacement for the ageing {{ship|French cruiser|Cosmao||2}}.\n\nIn 1903, she replaced the cruiser {{ship|French cruiser|Isly||2}} as division chief at the station of Newfoundland.\n\nDuring the [[First World War]], ''Lavoisier'' patrolled the Atlantic and the English Channel, before being sent in Eastern Mediterranean in 1915.\n\nIn 1919, she was appointed to the station of Syria.\n\nShe was struck in 1920, and sold for scrap the next year.\n\n\n==Design==\n{{main|Linois-class cruiser}}\n\n==Service history==\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book\n  | editor1-last = Gardiner\n  | editor1-first = Robert\n  | year = 1979\n  | title = Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1860\u20131905\n  | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-85177-133-5\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Gardiner}}\n  | url-access = registration\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/conwaysallworlds0000unse_l2e2\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  |editor1-last=Gardiner\n  |editor1-first=Robert\n  |editor2-last=Gray\n  |editor2-first=Randal\n  |title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships: 1906\u20131921\n  |year=1985\n  |location=Annapolis\n  |publisher=Naval Institute Press\n  |isbn=0-87021-907-3\n  |lastauthoramp=y\n  | ref = {{sfnRef|Gardiner & Gray}}\n  }}\n* {{cite journal\n  |last=Meirat\n  |first=Jean\n  |year=1975\n  |title=Details and Operational History of the Third-Class Cruiser Lavoisier\n  |journal=F. P. D. S. Newsletter\n  |publisher=F. P. D. S.\n  |location=Akron\n  |volume=III\n  |issue=3\n  |pages=20\u201323\n  |oclc=41554533\n  |ewd={{sfnref|Meirat}}\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ropp|authorlink=Theodore Ropp\n  | first = Theodore\n  | title = The Development of a Modern Navy: French Naval Policy, 1871\u20131904\n  | editor-last = Roberts\n  | editor-first = Stephen S.\n  | year = 1987\n  | location = Annapolis\n  | publisher = Naval Institute Press\n  | isbn = 978-0-87021-141-6\n  |ref={{sfnRef|Ropp}}\n  }}\n\n{{Linois-class cruiser}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lavoisier}}\n[[Category:Linois-class cruisers]]\n[[Category:Ships built in France]]\n[[Category:1896 ships]]\n[[Category:World War I cruisers of France]]\n", "name_user": "Parsecboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_cruiser_Lavoisier"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Little", "text_new": "{{For|the carpenter|Jimmy Little (carpenter)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Jimmy Little\n| image               = Jimmy-little.jpg\n| alt                 = A man is shown in an upper body shot, he sings at a microphone while holding an acoustic guitar.\n| caption             = Jimmy Little performing at Corroboree 2000\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = James Oswald Little\n| native_name         =\n| native_name_lang    = [[Yorta Yorta language|Yorta Yorta]]\n| alias               = Uncle Jimmy\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1937|03|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Cummeragunja Aboriginal Reserve]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| origin              =\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2012|4|2|1937|3|1|df=yes}}\n| death_place         = [[Dubbo]], New South Wales, Australia\n| genre               = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic]], [[Australian folk music#Folk rock|folk rock]], [[Australian country music|country]]\n| occupation          = Musician, actor, teacher\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar, harmonica\n| years_active        = 1951\u20132012\n| label               = [[Regal Zonophone Records|Regal Zonophone]], [[Festival Records|Festival]], Warner\n| associated_acts     = The Jimmy Little Trio\n| website             = {{URL|jimmylittle.com.au/}}<br/>{{URL|jlf.org.au/|Jimmy Little Foundation}}\n}}\n\n'''James Oswald Little''', [[Order of Australia|AO]] (1 March 1937{{spaced ndash}}2 April 2012)<ref name=\"Cashmere\">{{cite news|last=Cashmere|first=Paul|authorlink=Paul Cashmere|title=Jimmy Little Passes Away at 75|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/jimmy-little-passes-away-at-75-20120402|work=Noise11|publisher=The Noise Network (Paul Cashmere and Ros O'Gorman)|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref> was an [[Australian Aborigines|Australian Aboriginal]] musician, actor and teacher from the [[Yorta Yorta people]] and was raised on the [[Cummeragunja  Reserve]], New South Wales.\n\nFrom 1951 he had a career as a singer-songwriter and guitarist, which spanned six decades. For many years he was the main Aboriginal star on the Australian music scene. His music was influenced by [[Nat King Cole]] and American [[country music]] artist [[Jim Reeves]]. His gospel song \"Royal Telephone\" (1963) sold over 75,000 copies and his most popular album, ''Messenger'', peaked at No.&nbsp;26 in 1999 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]].\n\nAt the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1999]] Little was inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame]] and won an [[ARIA Award for Best Adult Contemporary Album]]. On [[Australia Day]] (26 January) 2004, he was made an Officer of the Order of Australia with the citation, \"For service to the entertainment industry as a singer, recording artist and songwriter and to the community through reconciliation and as an ambassador for Indigenous culture\".\n\nAs an actor, he appeared in the films ''[[Shadow of the Boomerang]]'' (1960) and ''[[Until the end of the World]]'' (1991), in the theatre production ''Black Cockatoos'' and in the opera ''Black River''. As a teacher, from 1985, he worked at the Eora Centre in [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]] and from 2000 was a guest lecturer at the [[University of Sydney]]'s Koori Centre.\n\nIn 1958 Little married Marjorie Rose Peters and they had a daughter, Frances Claire Peters-Little. Little was a diabetic with a heart condition and, in 2004, had a kidney transplant. After his transplant he established the Jimmy Little Foundation to promote indigenous health and diet. Marjorie died in July 2011. On 2 April 2012, Little died at his home in Dubbo, aged 75 years.<ref>{{Citation | last =Levy | first =Megan | title =Jimmy Little's long battle with illness ends | newspaper =The Sydney Morning Herald | date =2 April 2012 | url =http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/jimmy-littles-long-battle-with-illness-ends-20120402-1w80j.html | accessdate = 4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJames Oswald Little was born on 1 March 1937, a member of the [[Yorta Yorta people]] with his mother, Frances, a Yorta Yorta woman and his father, James Little Sr, from the [[Yuin people]].<ref name=\"Cashmere\"/><ref name=\"Murundak\">{{cite web | url = http://www.murundakdocumentary.com/artists/jimmy-little/ | title = Jimmy Little | publisher = Murundak | accessdate = 3 April 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120405003016/http://www.murundakdocumentary.com/artists/jimmy-little | archive-date = 5 April 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Little's totem is the [[Eastern long-necked turtle|long-necked turtle]].<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> Jimmy Little Sr. was a tap dancer, comedian, musician and singer who led his own vaudeville troupe along the Murray River during the 1930s and 1940s.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\">{{cite web | archiveurl = http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/14231/20120727-0512/www.howlspace.com.au/en/littlejimmy/littlejimmy.htm | url = http://www.howlspace.com.au/en/littlejimmy/littlejimmy.htm | title = Jimmy Little | last1 = Nimmervoll | first1 = Ed | authorlink1 = Ed Nimmervoll | publisher = Howlspace \u2013 The Living History of Our Music. White Room Electronic Publishing Pty Ltd | archivedate = 27 July 2012 | accessdate = 23 January 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Quinn\"/> His mother was a singer and yodeller who had joined Jimmy Sr.'s troupe.<ref name=\"Quinn\">{{cite news | url = http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/the-sweetest-man-i-ever-met-20120402-1w8vj.html | title = The Sweetest Man I Ever Met | last = Quinn | first = Karl | work = [[The Age]]  | date = 3 April 2012 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nLittle grew up, the eldest of seven children, on the Cummeragunja Aboriginal Reserve on the [[Murray River]] in New South Wales, about {{convert|30|km}} from [[Echuca]] in Victoria.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Shedden\">{{cite news | url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/arts/magic-of-sweet-voiced-entertainer/story-e6frg8n6-1226316857425 | title = Magic of Sweet-Voiced Entertainer | last = Shedden | first = Iain | work = [[The Australian]] | date = 3 April 2012 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> Little later recalled his upbringing, \"[my parents] taught me well about the value of life, freedom, love, respect, all those basic things that we need. As Vaudevillians, I loved them. It was part of my dream to follow in the footsteps of Mum and Dad. And I'm so proud that I was able to do that\".<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/talkingheads/txt/s1352846.htm | title = Transcripts \u2013 Jimmy Little | work = [[Talking Heads (Australian TV series)|Talking Heads]] with Peter Thompson | last = Thompson | first = Peter | authorlink = Peter Thompson (broadcaster) | publisher = Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) | date = 29 April 2005 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> He became a devout non-denominational Christian.<ref name=\"ASOClip3\">{{cite web | url = http://aso.gov.au/titles/documentaries/jimmy-littles-gentle-journey/clip3/ | title = ''Jimmy Little's Gentle Journey'' (2005) clip 3 | publisher = [[Australian Screen Online]] (ASO) ([[National Film and Sound Archive]]) | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> He is an uncle of writer, soprano, and composer [[Deborah Cheetham]] and older brother of the late Aboriginal author and singer-songwriter Betty Little.<ref>http://cpcabrisbane.org/Kasama/2007/V21n1/AroundDiningTable.htm</ref><ref>https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/A108535</ref> In February 1939, about 200 to 300 members of the mission participated in the [[Cummeragunja walk-off]] \u2013 in protest at the low standard living conditions.<ref name=\"CummeragunjaTime\">{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/missionvoices/cummeragunja/significant_events/default.htm | title = Cummergunja \u2013 Significant Events | publisher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) | accessdate = 3 April 2012 }}</ref> The Little family moved to his father's tribal land (near [[Wallaga Lake National Park|Wallaga Lake]]) and lived for some years on the New South Wales south coast at [[Nowra, New South Wales|Nowra]] and [[Moruya, New South Wales|Moruya]].<ref name=\"Thompson\"/><ref name=\"ListenHere\">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article44023956 | title = A Little Who May Go a Long Way | work = Teenager's Weekly. [[The Australian Women's Weekly]] | page = 7 | date = 16 September 1959 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nNot long after moving, Frances died from a tetanus infection after cutting her finger on an oyster shell.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> At the age of 13 Little was given a guitar and within a year he was playing at local concerts.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> When 16 years old he travelled to Sydney to perform on a radio programme, ''[[Australia's Amateur Hour]]''.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> In 1955 Little left home to live in Sydney and pursue a career in country music, he was influenced by [[Nat King Cole]], [[Johnny Mathis]] and [[Jim Reeves]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> His mellow style earned him the nicknames of \"the Balladeer\", \"Gentleman Jim\" and \"the Honey Voice\".<ref name=\"McFarlane\">{{Cite book | last1 = McFarlane | first1 = Ian | authorlink1 = Ian McFarlane | title = [[Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop]] | chapter = Encyclopedia entry for 'Jimmy Little' | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040930213156/http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=1053 | chapter-url = http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=1053 | accessdate = 3 April 2012 | archivedate = 30 September 2004 | year = 1999 | publisher = Allen & Unwin | location = St Leonards, New South Wales | isbn = 1865080721 }}</ref>\n\n===Early years: 1956\u20131979===\nIn 1956, Little signed with [[Regal Zonophone Records]] and released his first single, \"Mysteries of Life\"/\"Heartbreak Waltz\".<ref name=\"Thompson\"/><ref name=\"AAPObit\">{{cite journal | url = http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/vale-jimmy-little-legendary-aboriginal-muscian-dies.htm | title = Vale Jimmy Little: Beloved Musician Dies | last1 = [[Australian Associated Press]] (AAP) | last2 = ''Australian Geographic'' Staff | work = [[Australian Geographic]] | date = 3 April 2012 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120403025532/http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/vale-jimmy-little-legendary-aboriginal-muscian-dies.htm | archive-date = 3 April 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 1958, Little married fellow singer, Marjorie Rose Peters.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> By late 1959, Little was living in [[Granville, New South Wales|Granville]] with his wife and their daughter Frances Claire \u2013 he released the single, \"Frances Claire\", when she was 18&nbsp;months-old.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> It was issued on [[EMI]]'s [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia label]] and was soon followed by \"Give the Coloured Boy a Chance\", which had been written by his father \u2013 the first song released in Australia referring to indigenous issues and first both written and recorded by indigenous musicians.<ref name=\"MABio\">{{cite web | url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/people/1471131 | title = Jimmy Little | publisher = [[Music Australia]]. National Library of Australia | date = 5 August 2004 | accessdate = 15 January 2017 }}</ref> He worked at a towelling factory and supplemented his income with performances at concerts and dances, and TV appearances on ''[[Bandstand (Australia)|Bandstand]]''.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> Little signed with [[Festival Records]] and in September 1959, he had his first charting single, \"Danny Boy\", from the extended play, ''Jimmy Little Sings Ballads with a Beat'', which peaked at No.&nbsp;9 in Sydney.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/>\n\nIn February 1960, his next single was \"El Paso\", which reached No.&nbsp;12 in Sydney.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Little made his acting debut in the [[Billy Graham]] evangelical feature film ''Shadow of the Boomerang'' the same year.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref>Ross, Dick (1980). \"Shadow of the Boomerang\", in Pike, Andrew and Cooper, Ross. ''Oxford Australian Film 1900\u20131977''. Melbourne: Oxford University Press.</ref> Little had the role of Johnny, a devout [[Stockman (Australia)|stockman]] on a cattle station where his American employer's son Bob refers to him as \"that nigger\".<ref name=\"GrahamCrusade\"/> After Johnny dies, while saving Bob's life, from being gored by a wild boar, Bob has a religious conversion to Graham's cause.<ref name=\"GrahamCrusade\">{{cite web | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article55184838 | title = A Film of the Graham Crusade | work = Australian Women's Weekly | page = 5 | date = 12 April 1961 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> Little issued the title song as a single backed by \"Little by Little\".<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> In September 1961, he appeared on the radio program, ''[[Col Joye|Col Joye Show]]'', with fellow ''Bandstand'' regulars, [[Trisha Noble|Patsy Ann Noble]] and [[Judy Stone]].<ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite journal | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page4826343 | title = Listen Here \u2013 Col Joye Planning to go into Orbit | last = Ward | first = Kirsten | work = Teenager's Weekly. Australian Women's Weekly | page = 9 | date = 6 September 1961 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> By 1962, Little joined a touring stage production, ''All Coloured Show'' produced by Ted Quigg, and gained wider public exposure.<ref name=\"MABio\"/> In July 1963, he toured north west New South Wales with [[Robie Porter|Rob E.G.]], Noleen Batley and [[Lonnie Lee]] and was personally booked out till November.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite journal | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47511032 | title = Listen Here \u2013 New Girl Singer with Pretty Accent | last = Roberts | first = Diane | work = Teenager's Weekly. Australian Women's Weekly | page = 7 | date = 31 July 1963 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 1963, after 17 singles, Little issued his biggest hit with the gospel song, \"Royal Telephone\", based upon the [[Burl Ives]]' version.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Rogers\">{{cite journal | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47223946 | title = Popline \u2013 Gospel Hit for Jimmy | last = Rogers | first = Bob | authorlink = Bob Rogers (disc jockey) | work = Teenager's Weekly. Australian Women's Weekly | page = 10 | date = 4 December 1963 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> In November it peaked at No.&nbsp;1 in Sydney and No.&nbsp;3 in Melbourne.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> The following month ''[[Australian Women's Weekly]]''{{'}}s music writer, [[Bob Rogers (disc jockey)|Bob Rogers]] described it as \"a sincere ballad with a religious feeling\" and that \"[i]n only three weeks the record was rising to the top all over Australia, one of the fastest-selling records of the year\".<ref name=\"Rogers\"/> It was awarded 3\u00d7 [[Music recording sales certification|Gold certification]] by Festival Records and \"Best Male Vocal Disk\" (1963) in \"The Tunetable Awards\", Australia's first disk awards from a major radio source for home-produced disks.<ref name=\"MABio\"/><ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite journal|title=First Awards Go To Aussies| journal=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3|date=4 April 1964|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|page=3|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> In March 1964 the [[Barry Gibb]]-penned \"One Road\" reached No.&nbsp;19 in Sydney and No.&nbsp;30 in Melbourne.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Gibb was 17 years old when he wrote \"One Road\" and Little became one of the first artists to record a Gibb song.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> The magazine ''[[Everybody's (Australian magazine)|Everybody's]]'' named him Australian Pop Star of the Year.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Little was backed by the Jimmy Little Trio which had an all-indigenous line-up of Cyril Green,<ref>mistake is alleged to have been made in the Jimmy Little book where it stated the name of Cyril Peters. Further reference coming. Conversations with family and common knowledge in Armidale recognise Cyril Green as the band member.</ref> Doug Peters and Neville Thorn.<ref name=\"MABio\"/>\n\nLittle's final hit of the era came in September 1974 with \"Baby Blue\" which peaked at No.&nbsp;8 in Melbourne and No.&nbsp;37 in Sydney.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Further non-charting singles were released until 1978's \"Beautiful Woman\". From the end of the 1970s, Little turned from his musical career to focus on his family and becoming qualified as a teacher.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/><ref name=\"MABio\"/>\n\n===Middle years:1980\u20131999===\nBy the 1980s Little had turned to full-time acting, making his theatre debut in ''Black Cockatoos'' before appearing in director [[Wim Wenders]]' 1991 film ''[[Until the end of the World]]''.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> As well as appearing in Tracy Moffatt's ''Night Cries'' and [[Andrew Schultz]]'s opera ''Black River'', his teaching and community work earned him the title of [[NAIDOC]] [[NAIDOC Week|Aboriginal of the Year]] in 1989.<ref name=\"MABio\"/> After winning that award Little returned to working in the music industry.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/>\n\nIn 1992, Little performed at the [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]] on Parade and Kings of Country roadshows before releasing his 14th album, ''Yorta Yorta Man'', in 1994. The same year, he was inducted into [[Australian Roll of Renown]],<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> the highest honour an Australian country music artist can achieve.\n\n''Messenger'', a collection of contemporary songs reinterpreted through Little's smooth vocals, was released in June 1999 and peaked at No.&nbsp;26 nationally, selling over 20,000 copies.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> It had been organised by Brendan Gallagher (from [[Karma County]])<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> and featured covers of well-known songs by Australian artists: \"(Are You) The One I've Been Waiting For?\" by [[Nick Cave]], \"The Way I Made You Feel\" by [[Ed Kuepper]] and \"Randwick Bells\" by [[Paul Kelly (Australian musician)|Paul Kelly]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/>\n\nAt the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1999]] ''Messenger'' won Best Adult Contemporary Album and Little was inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> At [[Deadly Awards 1999|The Deadly Awards of 1999]] \u2013 the annual Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Music Awards \u2013 he won Best Male Artist of the Year and Best Single Release of the Year.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> By 2001 ''Messenger'' was certified by ARIA with a gold record for shipments of 35,000 units.<ref name=\"ARIACert2001\">{{Cite certification|region=Australia|type=album|certyear=2001}}</ref>\n\n===Later years:2000\u20132012===\nLittle returned in September 2001 with ''Resonate'', an album featuring songs written by Paul Kelly, [[Don Walker (musician)|Don Walker]], [[Bernard Fanning]] (from [[Powderfinger]]), Brendan Gallagher and [[Dave Graney]]. In 2002 Little won the Golden Gospel Award at the Australian Gospel Music Awards for his lifetime support of Australian gospel music. He also sang \"Happy Day' with Olivia Newton-John that year. In 2000 he was a guest of [[The Wiggles]] on their children's DVD ''Wiggly Wiggly World''.\n\nLittle released the album ''Down the Road'' for ABC Country in 2003. In 2004 he released his 34th album, ''Life's What You Make It'', a collection of distinctive and poignant versions of songs by contemporary artists as diverse as the [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[U2]], [[PJ Harvey]], [[Neil Young]], [[Brian Wilson]], [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Bruce Springsteen]].\n\nIn 2010 Little retired from performing.<ref name=\"Shedden\"/> On 2 April 2012 Little died of natural causes in [[Dubbo, New South Wales|Dubbo]], aged 75 years.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/>\n\n==Outreach and recognition==\n\nFrom 1985 Little taught and mentored indigenous music students at the Eora Centre in [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]] and from 2002 he was an ambassador for literacy and numeracy for the Department of Education. Since 2000 Little was a guest lecturer at the [[University of Sydney]]'s Koori Centre.<ref name=\"UniSyd\"/>\n\nAt the 1997 [[Mo Awards]], Little was awarded the John Campbell Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|title=22nd Mo Awards \u2013 1997|url=http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=630|work=moawards.com|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> for \"an outstanding contribution to the community beyond his normal career in the entertainment industry\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mo Awards Categories|url=http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=39|work=moawards.com|accessdate=5 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507225223/http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=39|archive-date=7 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Australia Day]] (26 January) 2004, Little was made an [[Order of Australia|Officer of the Order of Australia]] with the citation, \"For service to the entertainment industry as a singer, recording artist and songwriter and to the community through reconciliation and as an ambassador for Indigenous culture\".<ref name=\"AusHonours\">{{cite web | url = http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1055943&search_type=quick&showInd=true | title = Little, James Oswald | publisher = It's an Honour \u2013 Honours \u2013 Search Australian Honours. [[Government of Australia]] | date = 26 January 2004 | accessdate = 3 April 2012 }}</ref> Also that year he was named a [[Australian Living Treasures|Living National Treasure]]. In June 2005, on the last day of National Reconciliation Week, Little and composer [[Peter Sculthorpe]] were awarded honorary doctorates in music by the University of Sydney in recognition of \"their joint contribution to reconciliation between indigenous and non-indigenous Australians\".<ref name=\"UniSyd\">{{cite news | url = http://www.usyd.edu.au/news/84.html?newscategoryid=6&newsstoryid=195 | title = Music honours for Jimmy Little and Peter Sculthorpe | publisher = University of Sydney | date = 3 June 2005 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> Other honorary doctorates have been awarded to Little by [[Queensland University of Technology]] and [[Australian Catholic University]].<ref name=\"JimmyLittleFound\"/>\n\nLittle was diagnosed with kidney failure and, in 2004, after two years of self-administered dialysis he received a life-saving kidney transplant. The experience led him to launch the Jimmy Little Foundation in 2006 to help the many other indigenous Australians who are succumbing to kidney disease. The foundation works with patients in regional and remote Australia and partnered with the [[Fred Hollows]] Foundation in 2009 to develop a nutrition and education program for indigenous children to reduce the cycle of bad nutrition leading to [[diabetes]] which can lead to kidney failure.<ref name=\"JimmyLittleFound\">{{cite web | url = http://www.det.nt.gov.au%2F__data%2Fassets%2Fpdf_file%2F0005%2F19958%2FThumbsUp.pdf | title = Thumbs Up! Education Resource Launched in Darwin | last = Murphy | first = Emily | publisher = Jimmy Little Foundation, Department of Education and Training (DET) ([[Government of the Northern Territory]]) | date = 15 August 2009 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[APRA Awards of 2010]] Little was awarded the Ted Albert Award for 'Outstanding Services to Australian Music'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/apraawards/musicawards/history/2010Winners.aspx |title=2010 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards |publisher=[[Australasian Performing Right Association]] (APRA) |accessdate=24 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701075407/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/apraawards/musicawards/history/2010Winners.aspx |archivedate= 1 July 2010 }}</ref> \"Royal Telephone\" was featured on the [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] documentary, ''[[Buried Country|Buried Country: The Story of Aboriginal Country Music]]'' (2000) and its accompanying CD.\n\nActor and musician Michael Tuahine proposed a play based on the life of Jimmy Little. The play was written by [[Reg Cribb]] and called ''Country Song''; it won the 2013 Rodney Seaborn Playwright's Award for New Work. It was performed by the [[Queensland Theatre Company]] in the Cremorne Theatre at the [[Queensland Performing Arts Centre]] in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Country Song|url=http://www.queenslandtheatre.com.au/Whats-On/Mainstage-Season-2015/Country-Song|publisher=[[Queensland Theatre Country]]|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1958 Little married fellow singer, Marjorie Rose Peters and they had one child, Frances Claire Peters-Little (born ca. March 1958<!-- Said to be 18-months old in September 1959 -->),<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> who is a documentary film-maker, writer and historian.<ref name=\"ANU\">{{cite web | url = http://epress.anu.edu.au/author/frances-peters-little | title = Frances Peters-Little's information | publisher = Australian National University | accessdate = 5 April 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120321081405/http://epress.anu.edu.au/author/frances-peters-little | archive-date = 21 March 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 1990 Little was diagnosed with kidney disease, \"Unfortunately, I didn't get check-ups often enough or soon enough to realise the possibility that my kidneys could fail\".<ref name=\"Diabetes\">{{cite web | url = http://www.australiandiabetescouncil.com/Living-With-Diabetes/Real-People,-Real-Stories/Jimmy-Little.aspx | title = A Little Determination Goes a Long Way | publisher = Australian Diabetes Council | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> In 2002 he was diagnosed with kidney failure and was placed on dialysis and, in 2004, had a kidney transplant.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> As a result of immunosuppressants Little developed type 2 diabetes.<ref name=\"Diabetes\"/> He also developed a heart condition.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> Marjorie Rose Little died on 25 July 2011, aged 74, in Dubbo \u2013 she had been under medical care since early that year for an unspecified illness.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/><ref name=\"AAP2011\">{{cite news | url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/marjorie-rose-little-wife-of-entertainer-jimmy-little-dies/story-fn3dxity-1226101923592 | title = Marjorie Rose Little, Wife of Entertainer Jimmy Little Dies | work = The Australian | date = 26 July 2011 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> On 2 April 2012 Little died at his home in Dubbo, aged 75 years.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> He is survived by his daughter, Frances, and his grandson, James Henry Little.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> In 2005 Little told [[Peter Thompson (broadcaster)|Peter Thompson]], on the [[ABC1|ABC-TV]] program ''[[Talking Heads (Australian TV series)|Talking Heads]]'', how he would like to be remembered, \"I just want people to remember me as a nice person who was fair-minded and had a bit of talent that put it to good use.\"<ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''You'll Never Walk Alone'' ([[Festival Records]], 1960)\n* ''A Tree in The Meadow'' (Festival, February 1962)\n* ''By Request'' (Festival, 1963)\n* ''Sing to Glory'' (Festival, 1963)\n* ''Royal Telephone'' (Festival, 1964)\n* ''Encores'' (Festival, Festival, 1964)\n* ''Onward Christian Soldiers'' (Festival, 1964)\n* ''Jimmy Little Sings Country & Western Greats'' (Festival, 1965)\n* ''10th Anniversary'' (Festival, 1966)\n* ''Ballads and Strings'' (Festival, 1967)\n* ''New Songs from Jimmy Little'' (Festival, 1967)\n* ''The Best of Jimmy Little'' (Festival, 1968)\n* ''I Can't Stop Loving You'' (Festival, 1969)\n* ''Song to Glory'' (1969)\n* ''The Country Sound of Jimmy Little'' (1969)\n* ''Goodbye Old Rolf'' (1970)\n* ''Winterwood'' (Festival, 1972)\n* ''Waltzing Matilda'' (Festival, 1972)\n* ''Jimmy by Request'' (1973)\n* ''Country Boy, Country Hits'' (Festival, 1974)\n* ''All For Love'' (Festival, 1975)\n* ''Country Sounds'' (February 1975)\n* ''I Can't Stop Loving You'' (February 1975)\n* ''Jimmy Little Sings Country'' (1975)\n* ''Travellin' Minstrel Man'' (Festival, 1976)\n* ''The Best of Jimmy Little'' (Festival, 1977)\n* ''An Evening with Jimmy Little'' (1978) (double live album recorded at the [[Sydney Opera House]])\n* ''20 Golden Country Greats'' (Festival, 1979)\n* ''The Best of Jimmy Little'' (13 June 1994)\n* ''Yorta Yorta Man'' (Monitor, 1995)\n* ''Messenger'' (28 June 1999) alternative and classic Australian rock songs from the 1980s\n* ''Resonate'' (October 2001)\n* ''Passage 1959\u20132001: Jimmy Little Anthology'' (28 October 2002) Double CD anthology\n* ''Down the Road'' (1 September 2003)\n* ''Life's What You Make It'' (28 May 2004)\n* ''Jimmy Little: The Definitive Collection'' (9 July 2004)\n* ''Songman'' (7 December 2012)\n\n===EPs===\n* ''The Grandest Show of All'' (1957)\n* ''Jimmy Little Sings Ballads with a Beat'' (FX-5126 [[Festival Records]], 1959)\n* ''A Fool Such As I'' (1960)\n* ''Whispering Hope'' (1960)\n* ''Too Many Parties & Too Many Pals'' (1961)\n* ''A Man Called Peter'' (1962)\n* ''The Way of the Cross'' (1962)\n* ''Jimmy Little's Big Four'' (1962)\n* ''The Grandest Show of All'' (1963)\n* ''Royal Telephone'' (1963)\n* ''Old Time Religion'' (1964)\n* ''One Road'' (1964)\n* ''A Christmas Selection'' (1965)\n* ''Eternally'' (1965)\n* ''Lifeline'' (1965)\n* ''Ring, Bells Ring'' (1965)\n* ''A Christmas Selection'' (1966)\n* ''Goodbye Old Rolf'' (1970)\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n!| Chart Positions\n|-\n! <small>[[Kent Music Report|AUS]]<small>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1956\n|\"Mysteries of Life\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"It's Time To Pay\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Someday You're Gonna Call My Name\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Sweet Mama\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1957\n|\"Silver City Comet\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1959\n|\"Frances Claire\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Give The Coloured Boy a Chance\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"[[Danny Boy]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1960\n|\"[[El Paso (song)|El Paso]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|-\n|\"The Shadow of the Boomerang\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Bells of St. Marys\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Somebody's Pushing Me\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|97\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1961\n|\"Kissing Someone Else\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Silent Night\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1962\n|\"Little Green Valley\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1963\n|\"Pledge of Love\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Royal Telephone\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1964\n|\"Eternally\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|99\n|-\n|\"Lifeline\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"One Road\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|31\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1965\n|\"His Faith in Me\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Bimbombey\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Ring, Bells Ring\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1966\n|\"I Want To Be Free\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Too Many Times\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1968\n|\"Molly\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1969\n|\"[[I Can't Stop Loving You]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1970\n|\"Goodbye Old Rolf\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1973\n|\"There's a Heartache Following Me\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1974\n|\"Baby Blue\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1975\n|\"Ain't It Good (To Feel This Way)\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Goodbye Is Really Good at All\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||1976\n|\"Where The Blues of The Night Meets The Gold of The Day\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1978\n|\"Beautiful Woman\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"Beautiful Woman\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1999\n|\"Randwick Bells\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n|\"The Way I Made You Feel\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||2001\n|\"[[Bury Me Deep in Love]]\"<small>(with [[Kylie Minogue]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||2002\n|\"In a Field in France\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|-\n||2009\n|\"Royal Telephone\" <small>(Re-Recording)\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n|}\n\n== Other resources ==\n* ''Jimmy Little: Performing Artist'' (1997), a 26-minute videocassette produced and directed by Robin Hughes and Linda Kruger for [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS-TV]] and [[Film Australia]].<ref name=\"TroveHughes\">{{cite web | url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/9080956 | title = ''Jimmy Little : Performing Artist'' / Produced and Directed by Robin Hughes and Linda Kruger | last = [[Film Australia]] | publisher = [[Trove]]. (National Library of Australia) | quote = Singer and actor Jimmy Little talks about his childhood spent with his parents in a travelling vaudeville show, and his recording career with highlights including gold records, hits and awards, and his feelings about his role as an Aboriginal artist | year = 1997 | accessdate = 4 April 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Jimmy Little's Gentle Journey'' (2003), a 55-minute video written and directed by Sydney-based film-maker Sean Kennedy and released by Indigo Films and Warner Vision Australia.<ref name=\"TroveKennedy\">{{cite web | url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/12155169 | title = ''Jimmy Little's Gentle Journey'' &#91;videorecording&#93; | last = ABC-TV (Australia) | publisher = Trove. (National Library of Australia) | quote = From poverty and personal tragedy to Australia's first Aboriginal pop star, provides an intimate look at the life of a pioneering artist who defied incredible odds. This timely ABC TV program touchingly traces the trials and triumphs of a remarkable survivor celebrating 50 years in the business | year = 2003 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n* ''Jimmy Little'' (2005) a 26-minute DVD of a ''[[Talking Heads (Australian TV series)|Talking Heads]]'' interview by [[Peter Thompson (broadcaster)|Peter Thompson]] first broadcast on 29 April 2005.<ref name=\"TroveThompson\">{{cite web | url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/12155169 | title = ''Talking Heads: Jimmy Little'' &#91;videorecording&#93; | last1 = Thompson | first1 = Peter | last2 = ABC-TV (Australia) | publisher = Trove. (National Library of Australia) | quote = Peter Thompson talks to Australia's first Aboriginal pop star, Jimmy Little. It's more than 60 years since Jimmy Little first hit the road with his family and captured Australian hearts with his soulful voice. Revitalised after a recent kidney transplant, Jimmy is making tracks again, attracting new generations of fans. Jimmy Little is a member of the Yorta Yorta people and loves his native country with a passion. In this episode from ''[[Talking Heads (Australian TV series)|Talking Heads]]'', Jimmy strums his old guitar and sings a couple of songs for Peter Thompson | date = 29 April 2005 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jlf.org.au/ Jimmy Little Foundation website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050404163232/http://hem.passagen.se/honga/database/l/littlejimmy.html Jimmy Little] entry in the [[Australian Rock Database]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181019230948/http://colsearch.nfsa.afc.gov.au/nfsa/search/summary/summary.w3p;adv=yes;group=;groupequals=;page=0;parentid=;query=Number%3A352401%20%7C%20Number%3A352897%20%7C%20Number%3A351984%20%7C%20Number%3A565768%20%7C%20Number%3A358986;querytype=;resCount=10 Jimmy Little at the National Film and Sound Archive]\n* [http://aso.gov.au/titles/documentaries/jimmy-littles-gentle-journey/ ''Jimmy Little's Gentle Journey''] at [[Australian Screen Online]] \u2013 provides three video clips from the 2006 documentary, and [http://aso.gov.au/titles/documentaries/jimmy-littles-gentle-journey/notes/ curator's notes] by Romaine Moreton.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101030234511/http://creativespirits.info/resources/music/jimmy-little.html Discography]\n* {{IMDb name|1188003}}\n{{JC Williamson Award}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Commons category|Jimmy Little}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Little, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award winners]]\n[[Category:ARIA Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Australian Christians]]\n[[Category:Australian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Helpmann Award winners]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian actors]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian musicians]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the carpenter|Jimmy Little (carpenter)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Jimmy Little\n| image               = Jimmy-little.jpg\n| alt                 = A man is shown in an upper body shot, he sings at a microphone while holding an acoustic guitar.\n| caption             = Jimmy Little performing at Corroboree 2000\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = James Oswald Little\n| native_name         =\n| native_name_lang    = [[Yorta Yorta language|Yorta Yorta]]\n| alias               = Uncle Jimmy\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1937|03|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Cummeragunja Aboriginal Reserve]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| origin              =\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2012|4|2|1937|3|1|df=yes}}\n| death_place         = [[Dubbo]], New South Wales, Australia\n| genre               = [[Acoustic music|Acoustic]], [[Australian folk music#Folk rock|folk rock]], [[Australian country music|country]]\n| occupation          = Musician, actor, teacher\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar, harmonica\n| years_active        = 1951\u20132012\n| label               = [[Regal Zonophone Records|Regal Zonophone]], [[Festival Records|Festival]], Warner\n| associated_acts     = The Jimmy Little Trio\n| website             = {{URL|jimmylittle.com.au/}}<br/>{{URL|jlf.org.au/|Jimmy Little Foundation}}\n}}\n\n'''James Oswald Little''', [[Order of Australia|AO]] (1 March 1937{{spaced ndash}}2 April 2012)<ref name=\"Cashmere\">{{cite news|last=Cashmere|first=Paul|authorlink=Paul Cashmere|title=Jimmy Little Passes Away at 75|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/jimmy-little-passes-away-at-75-20120402|work=Noise11|publisher=The Noise Network (Paul Cashmere and Ros O'Gorman)|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref> was an [[Australian Aborigines|Australian Aboriginal]] musician, actor and teacher from the [[Yorta Yorta people]] and was raised on the [[Cummeragunja  Reserve]], New South Wales.\n\nFrom 1951 he had a career as a singer-songwriter and guitarist, which spanned six decades. For many years he was the main Aboriginal star on the Australian music scene. His music was influenced by [[Nat King Cole]] and American [[country music]] artist [[Jim Reeves]]. His gospel song \"Royal Telephone\" (1963) sold over 75,000 copies and his most popular album, ''Messenger'', peaked at No.&nbsp;26 in 1999 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]].\n\nAt the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1999]] Little was inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame]] and won an [[ARIA Award for Best Adult Contemporary Album]]. On [[Australia Day]] (26 January) 2004, he was made an Officer of the Order of Australia with the citation, \"For service to the entertainment industry as a singer, recording artist and songwriter and to the community through reconciliation and as an ambassador for Indigenous culture\".\n\nAs an actor, he appeared in the films ''[[Shadow of the Boomerang]]'' (1960) and ''[[Until the end of the World]]'' (1991), in the theatre production ''Black Cockatoos'' and in the opera ''Black River''. As a teacher, from 1985, he worked at the Eora Centre in [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]] and from 2000 was a guest lecturer at the [[University of Sydney]]'s Koori Centre.\n\nIn 1958 Little married Marjorie Rose Peters and they had a daughter, Frances Claire Peters-Little. Little was a diabetic with a heart condition and, in 2004, had a kidney transplant. After his transplant he established the Jimmy Little Foundation to promote indigenous health and diet. Marjorie died in July 2011. On 2 April 2012, Little died at his home in Dubbo, aged 75 years.<ref>{{Citation | last =Levy | first =Megan | title =Jimmy Little's long battle with illness ends | newspaper =The Sydney Morning Herald | date =2 April 2012 | url =http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/jimmy-littles-long-battle-with-illness-ends-20120402-1w80j.html | accessdate = 4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJames Oswald Little was born on 1 March 1937, a member of the [[Yorta Yorta people]] with his mother, Frances, a Yorta Yorta woman and his father, James Little Sr, from the [[Yuin people]].<ref name=\"Cashmere\"/><ref name=\"Murundak\">{{cite web | url = http://www.murundakdocumentary.com/artists/jimmy-little/ | title = Jimmy Little | publisher = Murundak | accessdate = 3 April 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120405003016/http://www.murundakdocumentary.com/artists/jimmy-little | archive-date = 5 April 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Little's totem is the [[Eastern long-necked turtle|long-necked turtle]].<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> Jimmy Little Sr. was a tap dancer, comedian, musician and singer who led his own vaudeville troupe along the Murray River during the 1930s and 1940s.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\">{{cite web | archiveurl = http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/14231/20120727-0512/www.howlspace.com.au/en/littlejimmy/littlejimmy.htm | url = http://www.howlspace.com.au/en/littlejimmy/littlejimmy.htm | title = Jimmy Little | last1 = Nimmervoll | first1 = Ed | authorlink1 = Ed Nimmervoll | publisher = Howlspace \u2013 The Living History of Our Music. White Room Electronic Publishing Pty Ltd | archivedate = 27 July 2012 | accessdate = 23 January 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Quinn\"/> His mother was a singer and yodeller who had joined Jimmy Sr.'s troupe.<ref name=\"Quinn\">{{cite news | url = http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/music/the-sweetest-man-i-ever-met-20120402-1w8vj.html | title = The Sweetest Man I Ever Met | last = Quinn | first = Karl | work = [[The Age]]  | date = 3 April 2012 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nLittle grew up, the eldest of seven children, on the Cummeragunja Aboriginal Reserve on the [[Murray River]] in New South Wales, about {{convert|30|km}} from [[Echuca]] in Victoria.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Shedden\">{{cite news | url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/arts/magic-of-sweet-voiced-entertainer/story-e6frg8n6-1226316857425 | title = Magic of Sweet-Voiced Entertainer | last = Shedden | first = Iain | work = [[The Australian]] | date = 3 April 2012 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> Little later recalled his upbringing, \"[my parents] taught me well about the value of life, freedom, love, respect, all those basic things that we need. As Vaudevillians, I loved them. It was part of my dream to follow in the footsteps of Mum and Dad. And I'm so proud that I was able to do that\".<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/talkingheads/txt/s1352846.htm | title = Transcripts \u2013 Jimmy Little | work = [[Talking Heads (Australian TV series)|Talking Heads]] with Peter Thompson | last = Thompson | first = Peter | authorlink = Peter Thompson (broadcaster) | publisher = Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) | date = 29 April 2005 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> He became a devout non-denominational Christian.<ref name=\"ASOClip3\">{{cite web | url = http://aso.gov.au/titles/documentaries/jimmy-littles-gentle-journey/clip3/ | title = ''Jimmy Little's Gentle Journey'' (2005) clip 3 | publisher = [[Australian Screen Online]] (ASO) ([[National Film and Sound Archive]]) | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> He is an uncle of writer, soprano, and composer [[Deborah Cheetham]] and older brother of the late Aboriginal author and singer-songwriter Betty Little.<ref>http://cpcabrisbane.org/Kasama/2007/V21n1/AroundDiningTable.htm</ref><ref>https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/A108535</ref> In February 1939, about 200 to 300 members of the mission participated in the [[Cummeragunja walk-off]] \u2013 in protest at the low standard living conditions.<ref name=\"CummeragunjaTime\">{{cite web | url = http://www.abc.net.au/missionvoices/cummeragunja/significant_events/default.htm | title = Cummergunja \u2013 Significant Events | publisher = [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC) | accessdate = 3 April 2012 }}</ref> The Little family moved to his father's tribal land (near [[Wallaga Lake National Park|Wallaga Lake]]) and lived for some years on the New South Wales south coast at [[Nowra, New South Wales|Nowra]] and [[Moruya, New South Wales|Moruya]].<ref name=\"Thompson\"/><ref name=\"ListenHere\">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article44023956 | title = A Little Who May Go a Long Way | work = Teenager's Weekly. [[The Australian Women's Weekly]] | page = 7 | date = 16 September 1959 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nNot long after moving, Frances died from a tetanus infection after cutting her finger on an oyster shell.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> At the age of 13 Little was given a guitar and within a year he was playing at local concerts.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> When 16 years old he travelled to Sydney to perform on a radio programme, ''[[Australia's Amateur Hour]]''.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> In 1955 Little left home to live in Sydney and pursue a career in country music, he was influenced by [[Nat King Cole]], [[Johnny Mathis]] and [[Jim Reeves]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> His mellow style earned him the nicknames of \"the Balladeer\", \"Gentleman Jim\" and \"the Honey Voice\".<ref name=\"McFarlane\">{{Cite book | last1 = McFarlane | first1 = Ian | authorlink1 = Ian McFarlane | title = [[Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop]] | chapter = Encyclopedia entry for 'Jimmy Little' | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040930213156/http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=1053 | chapter-url = http://www.whammo.com.au/encyclopedia.asp?articleid=1053 | accessdate = 3 April 2012 | archivedate = 30 September 2004 | year = 1999 | publisher = Allen & Unwin | location = St Leonards, New South Wales | isbn = 1865080721 }}</ref>\n\n===Early years: 1956\u20131979===\nIn 1956, Little signed with [[Regal Zonophone Records]] and released his first single, \"Mysteries of Life\"/\"Heartbreak Waltz\".<ref name=\"Thompson\"/><ref name=\"AAPObit\">{{cite journal | url = http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/vale-jimmy-little-legendary-aboriginal-muscian-dies.htm | title = Vale Jimmy Little: Beloved Musician Dies | last1 = [[Australian Associated Press]] (AAP) | last2 = ''Australian Geographic'' Staff | work = [[Australian Geographic]] | date = 3 April 2012 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120403025532/http://www.australiangeographic.com.au/journal/vale-jimmy-little-legendary-aboriginal-muscian-dies.htm | archive-date = 3 April 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 1958, Little married fellow singer, Marjorie Rose Peters.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> By late 1959, Little was living in [[Granville, New South Wales|Granville]] with his wife and their daughter Frances Claire \u2013 he released the single, \"Frances Claire\", when she was 18&nbsp;months-old.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> It was issued on [[EMI]]'s [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia label]] and was soon followed by \"Give the Coloured Boy a Chance\", which had been written by his father \u2013 the first song released in Australia referring to indigenous issues and first both written and recorded by indigenous musicians.<ref name=\"MABio\">{{cite web | url = http://trove.nla.gov.au/people/1471131 | title = Jimmy Little | publisher = [[Music Australia]]. National Library of Australia | date = 5 August 2004 | accessdate = 15 January 2017 }}</ref> He worked at a towelling factory and supplemented his income with performances at concerts and dances, and TV appearances on ''[[Bandstand (Australia)|Bandstand]]''.<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> Little signed with [[Festival Records]] and in September 1959, he had his first charting single, \"Danny Boy\", from the extended play, ''Jimmy Little Sings Ballads with a Beat'', which peaked at No.&nbsp;9 in Sydney.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/>\n\nIn February 1960, his next single was \"El Paso\", which reached No.&nbsp;12 in Sydney.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Little made his acting debut in the [[Billy Graham]] evangelical feature film ''Shadow of the Boomerang'' the same year.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref>Ross, Dick (1980). \"Shadow of the Boomerang\", in Pike, Andrew and Cooper, Ross. ''Oxford Australian Film 1900\u20131977''. Melbourne: Oxford University Press.</ref> Little had the role of Johnny, a devout [[Stockman (Australia)|stockman]] on a cattle station where his American employer's son Bob refers to him as \"that nigger\".<ref name=\"GrahamCrusade\"/> After Johnny dies, while saving Bob's life, from being gored by a wild boar, Bob has a religious conversion to Graham's cause.<ref name=\"GrahamCrusade\">{{cite web | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article55184838 | title = A Film of the Graham Crusade | work = Australian Women's Weekly | page = 5 | date = 12 April 1961 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> Little issued the title song as a single backed by \"Little by Little\".<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> In September 1961, he appeared on the radio program, ''[[Col Joye|Col Joye Show]]'', with fellow ''Bandstand'' regulars, [[Trisha Noble|Patsy Ann Noble]] and [[Judy Stone]].<ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite journal | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-page4826343 | title = Listen Here \u2013 Col Joye Planning to go into Orbit | last = Ward | first = Kirsten | work = Teenager's Weekly. Australian Women's Weekly | page = 9 | date = 6 September 1961 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> By 1962, Little joined a touring stage production, ''All Coloured Show'' produced by Ted Quigg, and gained wider public exposure.<ref name=\"MABio\"/> In July 1963, he toured north west New South Wales with [[Robie Porter|Rob E.G.]], Noleen Batley and [[Lonnie Lee]] and was personally booked out till November.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite journal | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47511032 | title = Listen Here \u2013 New Girl Singer with Pretty Accent | last = Roberts | first = Diane | work = Teenager's Weekly. Australian Women's Weekly | page = 7 | date = 31 July 1963 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 1963, after 17 singles, Little issued his biggest hit with the gospel song, \"Royal Telephone\", based upon the [[Burl Ives]]' version.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/><ref name=\"Rogers\">{{cite journal | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47223946 | title = Popline \u2013 Gospel Hit for Jimmy | last = Rogers | first = Bob | authorlink = Bob Rogers (disc jockey) | work = Teenager's Weekly. Australian Women's Weekly | page = 10 | date = 4 December 1963 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> In November it peaked at No.&nbsp;1 in Sydney and No.&nbsp;3 in Melbourne.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> The following month ''[[Australian Women's Weekly]]''{{'}}s music writer, [[Bob Rogers (disc jockey)|Bob Rogers]] described it as \"a sincere ballad with a religious feeling\" and that \"[i]n only three weeks the record was rising to the top all over Australia, one of the fastest-selling records of the year\".<ref name=\"Rogers\"/> It was awarded 3\u00d7 [[Music recording sales certification|Gold certification]] by Festival Records and \"Best Male Vocal Disk\" (1963) in \"The Tunetable Awards\", Australia's first disk awards from a major radio source for home-produced disks.<ref name=\"MABio\"/><ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite journal|title=First Awards Go To Aussies| journal=Billboard|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA3|date=4 April 1964|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|page=3|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> In March 1964 the [[Barry Gibb]]-penned \"One Road\" reached No.&nbsp;19 in Sydney and No.&nbsp;30 in Melbourne.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Gibb was 17 years old when he wrote \"One Road\" and Little became one of the first artists to record a Gibb song.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> The magazine ''[[Everybody's (Australian magazine)|Everybody's]]'' named him Australian Pop Star of the Year.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Little was backed by the Jimmy Little Trio which had an all-indigenous line-up of Cyril Green,<ref>mistake is alleged to have been made in the Jimmy Little book where it stated the name of Cyril Peters. Further reference coming. Conversations with family and common knowledge in Armidale recognise Cyril Green as the band member.</ref> Doug Peters and Neville Thorn.<ref name=\"MABio\"/>\n\nLittle's final hit of the era came in September 1974 with \"Baby Blue\" which peaked at No.&nbsp;8 in Melbourne and No.&nbsp;37 in Sydney.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> Further non-charting singles were released until 1978's \"Beautiful Woman\". From the end of the 1970s, Little turned from his musical career to focus on his family and becoming qualified as a teacher.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/><ref name=\"MABio\"/>\n\n===Middle years:1980\u20131999===\nBy the 1980s Little had turned to full-time acting, making his theatre debut in ''Black Cockatoos'' before appearing in director [[Wim Wenders]]' 1991 film ''[[Until the end of the World]]''.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> As well as appearing in Tracy Moffatt's ''Night Cries'' and [[Andrew Schultz]]'s opera ''Black River'', his teaching and community work earned him the title of [[NAIDOC]] [[NAIDOC Week|Aboriginal of the Year]] in 1989.<ref name=\"MABio\"/> After winning that award Little returned to working in the music industry.<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/>\n\nIn 1992, Little performed at the [[Tamworth, New South Wales|Tamworth]] on Parade and Kings of Country roadshows before releasing his 14th album, ''Yorta Yorta Man'', in 1994. The same year, he was inducted into [[Australian Roll of Renown]],<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> the highest honour an Australian country music artist can achieve.\n\n''Messenger'', a collection of contemporary songs reinterpreted through Little's smooth vocals, was released in June 1999 and peaked at No.&nbsp;26 nationally, selling over 20,000 copies.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> It had been organised by Brendan Gallagher (from [[Karma County]])<ref name=\"Nimmervoll\"/> and featured covers of well-known songs by Australian artists: \"(Are You) The One I've Been Waiting For?\" by [[Nick Cave]], \"The Way I Made You Feel\" by [[Ed Kuepper]] and \"Randwick Bells\" by [[Paul Kelly (Australian musician)|Paul Kelly]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/>\n\nAt the [[ARIA Music Awards of 1999]] ''Messenger'' won Best Adult Contemporary Album and Little was inducted into the [[ARIA Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> At [[Deadly Awards 1999|The Deadly Awards of 1999]] \u2013 the annual Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Music Awards \u2013 he won Best Male Artist of the Year and Best Single Release of the Year.<ref name=\"McFarlane\"/> By 2001 ''Messenger'' was certified by ARIA with a gold record for shipments of 35,000 units.<ref name=\"ARIACert2001\">{{Cite certification|region=Australia|type=album|certyear=2001}}</ref>\n\n===Later years:2000\u20132012===\nLittle returned in September 2001 with ''Resonate'', an album featuring songs written by Paul Kelly, [[Don Walker (musician)|Don Walker]], [[Bernard Fanning]] (from [[Powderfinger]]), Brendan Gallagher and [[Dave Graney]]. In 2002 Little won the Golden Gospel Award at the Australian Gospel Music Awards for his lifetime support of Australian gospel music. He also sang \"Happy Day' with Olivia Newton-John that year. In 2000 he was a guest of [[The Wiggles]] on their children's DVD ''Wiggly Wiggly World''.\n\nLittle released the album ''Down the Road'' for ABC Country in 2003. In 2004 he released his 34th album, ''Life's What You Make It'', a collection of distinctive and poignant versions of songs by contemporary artists as diverse as the [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]], [[U2]], [[PJ Harvey]], [[Neil Young]], [[Brian Wilson]], [[Elvis Costello]] and [[Bruce Springsteen]].\n\nIn 2010 Little retired from performing.<ref name=\"Shedden\"/> On 2 April 2012 Little died of natural causes in [[Dubbo, New South Wales|Dubbo]], aged 75 years.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/>\n\n==Outreach and recognition==\n\nFrom 1985 Little taught and mentored indigenous music students at the Eora Centre in [[Redfern, New South Wales|Redfern]] and from 2002 he was an ambassador for literacy and numeracy for the Department of Education. Since 2000 Little was a guest lecturer at the [[University of Sydney]]'s Koori Centre.<ref name=\"UniSyd\"/>\n\nAt the 1997 [[Mo Awards]], Little was awarded the John Campbell Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|title=22nd Mo Awards \u2013 1997|url=http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=630|work=moawards.com|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> for \"an outstanding contribution to the community beyond his normal career in the entertainment industry\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mo Awards Categories|url=http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=39|work=moawards.com|accessdate=5 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507225223/http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=39|archive-date=7 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Australia Day]] (26 January) 2004, Little was made an [[Order of Australia|Officer of the Order of Australia]] with the citation, \"For service to the entertainment industry as a singer, recording artist and songwriter and to the community through reconciliation and as an ambassador for Indigenous culture\".<ref name=\"AusHonours\">{{cite web | url = http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1055943&search_type=quick&showInd=true | title = Little, James Oswald | publisher = It's an Honour \u2013 Honours \u2013 Search Australian Honours. [[Government of Australia]] | date = 26 January 2004 | accessdate = 3 April 2012 }}</ref> Also that year he was named a [[Australian Living Treasures|Living National Treasure]]. In June 2005, on the last day of National Reconciliation Week, Little and composer [[Peter Sculthorpe]] were awarded honorary doctorates in music by the University of Sydney in recognition of \"their joint contribution to reconciliation between indigenous and non-indigenous Australians\".<ref name=\"UniSyd\">{{cite news | url = http://www.usyd.edu.au/news/84.html?newscategoryid=6&newsstoryid=195 | title = Music honours for Jimmy Little and Peter Sculthorpe | publisher = University of Sydney | date = 3 June 2005 | accessdate = 4 April 2012 }}</ref> Other honorary doctorates have been awarded to Little by [[Queensland University of Technology]] and [[Australian Catholic University]].<ref name=\"JimmyLittleFound\"/>\n\nLittle was diagnosed with kidney failure and, in 2004, after two years of self-administered dialysis he received a life-saving kidney transplant. The experience led him to launch the Jimmy Little Foundation in 2006 to help the many other indigenous Australians who are succumbing to kidney disease. The foundation works with patients in regional and remote Australia and partnered with the [[Fred Hollows]] Foundation in 2009 to develop a nutrition and education program for indigenous children to reduce the cycle of bad nutrition leading to [[diabetes]] which can lead to kidney failure.<ref name=\"JimmyLittleFound\">{{cite web | url = http://www.det.nt.gov.au%2F__data%2Fassets%2Fpdf_file%2F0005%2F19958%2FThumbsUp.pdf | title = Thumbs Up! Education Resource Launched in Darwin | last = Murphy | first = Emily | publisher = Jimmy Little Foundation, Department of Education and Training (DET) ([[Government of the Northern Territory]]) | date = 15 August 2009 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[APRA Awards of 2010]] Little was awarded the Ted Albert Award for 'Outstanding Services to Australian Music'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/apraawards/musicawards/history/2010Winners.aspx |title=2010 Winners \u2013 APRA Music Awards |publisher=[[Australasian Performing Right Association]] (APRA) |accessdate=24 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701075407/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/apraawards/musicawards/history/2010Winners.aspx |archivedate= 1 July 2010 }}</ref> \"Royal Telephone\" was featured on the [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] documentary, ''[[Buried Country|Buried Country: The Story of Aboriginal Country Music]]'' (2000) and its accompanying CD.\n\nActor and musician Michael Tuahine proposed a play based on the life of Jimmy Little. The play was written by [[Reg Cribb]] and called ''Country Song''; it won the 2013 Rodney Seaborn Playwright's Award for New Work. It was performed by the [[Queensland Theatre Company]] in the Cremorne Theatre at the [[Queensland Performing Arts Centre]] in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Country Song|url=http://www.queenslandtheatre.com.au/Whats-On/Mainstage-Season-2015/Country-Song|publisher=[[Queensland Theatre Country]]|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1958 Little married fellow singer, Marjorie Rose Peters and they had one child, Frances Claire Peters-Little (born ca. March 1958<!-- Said to be 18-months old in September 1959 -->),<ref name=\"ListenHere\"/> who is a documentary film-maker, writer and historian.<ref name=\"ANU\">{{cite web | url = http://epress.anu.edu.au/author/frances-peters-little | title = Frances Peters-Little's information | publisher = Australian National University | accessdate = 5 April 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120321081405/http://epress.anu.edu.au/author/frances-peters-little | archive-date = 21 March 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In 1990 Little was diagnosed with kidney disease, \"Unfortunately, I didn't get check-ups often enough or soon enough to realise the possibility that my kidneys could fail\".<ref name=\"Diabetes\">{{cite web | url = http://www.australiandiabetescouncil.com/Living-With-Diabetes/Real-People,-Real-Stories/Jimmy-Little.aspx | title = A Little Determination Goes a Long Way | publisher = Australian Diabetes Council | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> In 2002 he was diagnosed with kidney failure and was placed on dialysis and, in 2004, had a kidney transplant.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> As a result of immunosuppressants Little developed type 2 diabetes.<ref name=\"Diabetes\"/> He also developed a heart condition.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> Marjorie Rose Little died on 25 July 2011, aged 74, in Dubbo \u2013 she had been under medical care since early that year for an unspecified illness.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/><ref name=\"AAP2011\">{{cite news | url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/marjorie-rose-little-wife-of-entertainer-jimmy-little-dies/story-fn3dxity-1226101923592 | title = Marjorie Rose Little, Wife of Entertainer Jimmy Little Dies | work = The Australian | date = 26 July 2011 | accessdate = 5 April 2012 }}</ref> On 2 April 2012 Little died at his home in Dubbo, aged 75 years.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> He is survived by his daughter, Frances, and his grandson, James Henry Little.<ref name=\"AAPObit\"/> In 2005 Little told [[Peter Thompson (broadcaster)|Peter Thompson]], on the [[ABC1|ABC-TV]] program ''[[Talking Heads (Australian TV series)|Talking Heads]]'', how he would like to be remembered, \"I just want people to remember me as a nice person who was fair-minded and had a bit of talent that put it to good use.\"<ref name=\"Thompson\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* ''You'll Never Walk Alone'' ([[Festival Records]], 1960)\n* ''A Tree in The Meadow'' (Festival, February 1962)\n* ''By Request'' (Festival, 1963)\n* ''Sing to Glory'' (Festival, 1963)\n* ''Royal Telephone'' (Festival, 1964)\n* ''Encores'' (Festival, Festival, 1964)\n* ''Onward Christian Soldiers'' (Festival, 1964)\n* ''Jimmy Little Sings Country & Western Greats'' (Festival, 1965)\n* ''10th Anniversary'' (Festival, 1966)\n* ''Ballads and Strings'' (Festival, 1967)\n* ''New Songs from Jimmy Little'' (Festival, 1967)\n* ''The Best of Jimmy Little'' (Festival, 1968)\n* ''I Can't Stop Loving You'' (Festival, 1969)\n* ''Song to Glory'' (1969)\n* ''The Country Sound of Jimmy Little'' (1969)\n* ''Goodbye Old Rolf'' (1970)\n* ''Winterwood'' (Festival, 1972)\n* ''Waltzing Matilda'' (Festival, 1972)\n* ''Jimmy by Request'' (1973)\n* ''Country Boy, Country Hits'' (Festival, 1974)\n* ''All For Love'' (Festival, 1975)\n* ''Country Sounds'' (February 1975)\n* ''I Can't Stop Loving You'' (February 1975)\n* ''Jimmy Little Sings Country'' (1975)\n* ''Travellin' Minstrel Man'' (Festival, 1976)\n* ''The Best of Jimmy Little'' (Festival, 1977)\n* ''An Evening with Jimmy Little'' (1978) (double live album recorded at the [[Sydney Opera House]])\n* ''20 Golden Country Greats'' (Festival, 1979)\n* ''The Best of Jimmy Little'' (13 June 1994)\n* ''Yorta Yorta Man'' (Monitor, 1995)\n* ''Messenger'' (28 June 1999) alternative and classic Australian rock songs from the 1980s\n* ''Resonate'' (October 2001)\n* ''Passage 1959\u20132001: Jimmy Little Anthology'' (28 October 2002) Double CD anthology\n* ''Down the Road'' (1 September 2003)\n* ''Life's What You Make It'' (28 May 2004)\n* ''Jimmy Little: The Definitive Collection'' (9 July 2004)\n* ''Songman'' (7 December 2012)\n\n===EPs===\n* ''The Grandest Show of All'' (1957)\n* ''Jimmy Little Sings Ballads with a Beat'' (FX-5126 [[Festival Records]], 1959)\n* ''A Fool Such As I'' (1960)\n* ''Whispering Hope'' (1960)\n* ''Too Many Parties & Too Many Pals'' (1961)\n* ''A Man Called Peter'' (1962)\n* ''The Way of the Cross'' (1962)\n* ''Jimmy Little's Big Four'' (1962)\n* ''The Grandest Show of All'' (1963)\n* ''Royal Telephone'' (1963)\n* ''Old Time Religion'' (1964)\n* ''One Road'' (1964)\n* ''A Christmas Selection'' (1965)\n* ''Eternally'' (1965)\n* ''Lifeline'' (1965)\n* ''Ring, Bells Ring'' (1965)\n* ''A Christmas Selection'' (1966)\n* ''Goodbye Old Rolf'' (1970)\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! colspan=\"1\"| Chart Positions\n|-\n! <small>[[Kent Music Report|AUS]]<small>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1956\n|\"Mysteries of Life\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"It's Time To Pay\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"Someday You're Gonna Call My Name\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"Sweet Mama\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|1957\n|\"Silver City Comet\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|1959\n|\"Frances Claire\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"Give The Coloured Boy a Chance\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"[[Danny Boy]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|1960\n|\"[[El Paso (song)|El Paso]]\"\n|align=\"center\"|21\n|-\n|\"The Shadow of the Boomerang\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"Bells of St. Marys\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"Somebody's Pushing Me\"\n|align=\"center\"|97\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|1961\n|\"Kissing Someone Else\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|\"Silent Night\"\n|align=\"center\"|-\n|-\n|rows