013), 177\u2013200.\n* {{cite book|url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/geology/publications/bul/612/index.htm |title=Guidebook of the Western United States, Part B. The Overland Route |author1=Lee, Willis T. |author2=Ralph W. Stone |author3=Hoyt S. Gale |last-author-amp=yes |year=1916 |publisher=USGS Bulletin 612 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505042503/http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/geology/publications/bul/612/index.htm |archivedate=May 5, 2012 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Sandler |first1=Martin W. |title=Iron Rails, Iron Men, and the race to link the nation: The story of the transcontinental railroad |date=2015 |publisher=Candlewick Press |location=Somerville, MA |isbn=978-0-7636-6527-2}}\n* White, Richard. '' Railroaded: The Transcontinentals and the Making of Modern America'' (2010)\n* Willumson, Glenn. ''Iron Muse: Photographing the Transcontinental Railroad'' (University of California Press; 2013) 242 pages; studies the production, distribution, and publication of images of the railroad in the 19th and early 20th centuries.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|First Transcontinental Railroad}}\n\nFor maps and railroad pictures of this era shortly after the advent of [[History of photography|photography]] see:\n\n* [http://cprr.org/Museum/index.html Central Pacific Railroad Photographic History Museum]\n* [http://www.cprr.org/Museum/Maps/ CPRR Railroad Map collection/museum]\n* [http://www.cprr.org/Museum/Maps/_cprr_map.html 1871 CPRR & UPRR Overland Railroad Map] \"Map of the Central Pacific Railroad and its Connections\" published in the California Mail Bag San Francisco News Letter and California Advertiser, Vol. 1, No. 4, Oct\u2013Nov. 1871. accessed May 1, 2013.\n* Union Pacific Railroad picture Museum [https://web.archive.org/web/20170812212711/http://www.up.com/aboutup/history/photos/railroad_construction/index.htm Excursion to the 100th Meridian \u2013 1866] accessed March 1, 2013.\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/pacifictourist1881willuoft The Pacific Tourist]''  Williams, Henry T.; published by Adams & Bishop, New York, 1881 ed. Gives insights to travel in the late 1880s on the transcontinental railroad.\n* [http://edsitement.neh.gov/lesson-plan/i-hear-locomotives-impact-transcontinental-railroad \"I Hear the Locomotives: The Impact of the Transcontinental Railroad\"]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/gosp/ Golden Spike National Historical Site in Utah]\n* [http://CPRR.org Central Pacific Railroad Photographic History Museum]\n* [http://www.uprr.com/aboutup/history/ Union Pacific Railroad History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070628203843/http://bushong.net/dawn/about/college/ids100/ The Transcontinental Railroad]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/rr/program/bib/ourdocs/PacificRail.html Pacific Railway Act and related resources at the Library of Congress]\n* [http://cprr.org/Museum/Chinese.html Chinese-American Contribution to transcontinental railroad]\n* [http://railroad.lindahall.org Linda Hall Library's Transcontinental Railroad educational site with free, full-text access to 19th century American railroad periodicals]\n* [https://www.newspapers.com/topics/industrial-gilded-ages/transcontinental-railroad/ Newspaper articles and clippings about the Transcontinental Railroad at Newspapers.com]\n; Maps\n* [https://www.loc.gov/collection/railroad-maps-1828-to-1900/?q=continental%20railway&fi=subject Route map at the Library of Congress]\n* [http://www.up.com/cs/groups/public/documents/up_pdf_nativedocs/pdf_eot_historical_up_maps.pdf Map of Union Pacific Railroad with Dates]\n* [http://www.abandonedrails.com/Original_Transcontinental_Railroad Abandoned route of the transcontinental railroad in Utah (with map)]\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{North America in topic|Rail transport in}}\n{{US railroad lists}}\n{{Omaha Railroads|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:First Transcontinental Railroad|01]]\n[[Category:1860s in California]]\n[[Category:1869 in the United States]]\n[[Category:American 