{"title_page": "Chow Kit", "text_new": "{{Coord|3|9|47.9|N|101|41|48.8|E|display=title}}\n[[Image:Chow Kit (southward), Kuala Lumpur.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Jalan Tuanku Abdul Rahman in Chow Kit]]\n\n'''Chow Kit''' is a suburb in central [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]. It is located around Jalan Chow Kit (Chow Kit Road) and is enclosed by the parallel streets of Jalan Raja Laut and Jalan Tuanku Abdul Rahman. It is named after Loke Chow Kit (\u9678\u79cb\u5091) a well-known miner, municipal councilor, public official, and also the first local owner of a department store - Chow Kit & Co \u2013 which was the largest in KL at the time.<ref name=\"chowkit\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.malaysiandigest.com/features/77922-malaysian-road-names-who-is-who.html |title=Malaysian Road Names: Who's Who? |access-date=2017-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630181136/http://www.malaysiandigest.com/features/77922-malaysian-road-names-who-is-who.html |archive-date=2017-06-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Today the area features a large [[Indonesia]]n ([[Javanese people|Javanese]]) community, and more recently, a small [[Ethnic groups of Africa|African]] community. There is a [[Pasar malam|night market]] also known as ''Bundle Chow Kit'' along Lorong Haji Taib which is known for the sale of [[Used good#Used clothes|used clothing]] and accessories.<ref>[http://www.bharian.com.my/Current_News/HM/Thursday/Santai/20061109124115/pp_index_html \"Bundle Chow Kit tetap hebat\"], ''Harian Metro''. ''Bernama''. Accessed 19 July 2007.{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Wet market==\nA daily [[Pasar pagi|wet market]] known as Bazaar Baru Chow Kit is the largest wet market in Kuala Lumpur, and a tourist attraction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/destination/chow%20kit%20market.html |title=Chow Kit Market|accessdate=2014-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706220844/http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/destination/chow%20kit%20market.html |archivedate=2007-07-06 }}</ref> A wide variety of [[fish]] and [[seafood]] products are available for customers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Photographs of Chow Kit wet market|url=https://independent-travellers.com/malaysia/kuala_lumpur/chow_kit_market/|website=Independent Travellers|publisher=independent-travellers.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Red-light district==\nChow Kit has traditionally been known as one of the major [[red-light district]]s in [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanjugtha |first1=V |title=Rejuvenating Chow Kit |url=http://www.focusmalaysia.my/Assets/rejuvenating-chow-kit |website=Focus Malaysia |accessdate=31 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422121504/https://focusmalaysia.my/Assets/rejuvenating-chow-kit|archive-date=22 April 2019}}</ref> Many of the [[prostitute]]s are daughters of prostitutes and have grown up in the area.<ref>{{Cite news | year = 2006 | url = http://thestaronline.com/news/story.asp?file=/2006/7/9/nation/14761340&sec=nation | title = Uncertain future for Chow Kit children | work = thestaronline.com | accessdate = 21 July 2006 | archive-date = 17 February 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120217094823/http://thestaronline.com/news/story.asp?file=%2F2006%2F7%2F9%2Fnation%2F14761340&sec=nation | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Malaysian director Justin Ong's 2013 film, ''Ida's choice'', is about a young woman in the red-light district.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ida's choice |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/witness/2013/03/201332512410892945.html |website=www.aljazeera.com |accessdate=31 January 2019 |date=26 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe [[KL Monorail]] [[Chow Kit Monorail station]] is situated in this area, and the [[Ampang Line]] [[PWTC LRT station]] is located nearby.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Chow Kit Road became the subject of the hit song, ''Chow Kit Road'', made famous by the late [[Sudirman Arshad]].<ref name=\"chowkit\"/> Sudirman held an open-air concert on the road in 1986 to a 100,000-strong audience.<ref name=\"sudirmanconcert\">[http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2013/04/05/good-ol-charm-of-jalan-chow-kit/ Good ol\u2019 charm of Jalan Chow Kit]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SHOPPING_2_0042.jpg|The wet market\nFile:MURTABAK_1_0031.jpg|Murtabak (pancake) seller\nFile:CHICKEN_1_0050.jpg|Chicken meat in Chow Kit\nFile:ANCHOVY_1_0058.jpg|Small-sized anchovies in Chow Kit\nFile:Bazaar Baru Chow Kit 631.jpg|[[Carambola]] \nFile:Bazaar Baru Chow Kit 632.jpg|[[Pitaya]]\nFile:Bazaar Baru Chow Kit 634.jpg|[[Durian]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Chow Kit}}\n\n{{Etnic Enclaves in Malaysia}}\n{{Greater Kuala Lumpur}}\n\n[[Category:African diaspora in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Suburbs in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Indonesian diaspora in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Red-light districts in Malaysia]]\n\n\n{{malaysia-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|3|9|47.9|N|101|41|48.8|E|display=title}}\n[[Image:Chow Kit (southward), Kuala Lumpur.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Jalan Tuanku Abdul Rahman in Chow Kit]]\n\n'''Chow Kit''' is a sub-district in central [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]. It is located around Jalan Chow Kit (Chow Kit Road) and is enclosed by the parallel streets of Jalan Raja Laut and Jalan Tuanku Abdul Rahman. It is named after Loke Chow Kit (\u9678\u79cb\u5091) a well-known miner, municipal councilor, public official, and also the first local owner of a department store - Chow Kit & Co \u2013 which was the largest in KL at the time.<ref name=\"chowkit\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.malaysiandigest.com/features/77922-malaysian-road-names-who-is-who.html |title=Malaysian Road Names: Who's Who? |access-date=2017-01-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630181136/http://www.malaysiandigest.com/features/77922-malaysian-road-names-who-is-who.html |archive-date=2017-06-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Today the area features a large [[Indonesia]]n ([[Javanese people|Javanese]]) community, and more recently, a small [[Ethnic groups of Africa|African]] community. There is a [[Pasar malam|night market]] also known as ''Bundle Chow Kit'' along Lorong Haji Taib which is known for the sale of [[Used good#Used clothes|used clothing]] and accessories.<ref>[http://www.bharian.com.my/Current_News/HM/Thursday/Santai/20061109124115/pp_index_html \"Bundle Chow Kit tetap hebat\"], ''Harian Metro''. ''Bernama''. Accessed 19 July 2007.{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Wet market==\nA daily [[Pasar pagi|wet market]] known as Bazaar Baru Chow Kit is the largest wet market in Kuala Lumpur, and a tourist attraction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/destination/chow%20kit%20market.html |title=Chow Kit Market|accessdate=2014-10-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706220844/http://www.virtualmalaysia.com/destination/chow%20kit%20market.html |archivedate=2007-07-06 }}</ref> A wide variety of [[fish]] and [[seafood]] products are available for customers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Photographs of Chow Kit wet market|url=https://independent-travellers.com/malaysia/kuala_lumpur/chow_kit_market/|website=Independent Travellers|publisher=independent-travellers.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Red-light district==\nChow Kit has traditionally been known as one of the major [[red-light district]]s in Kuala Lumpur.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanjugtha |first1=V |title=Rejuvenating Chow Kit |url=http://www.focusmalaysia.my/Assets/rejuvenating-chow-kit |website=Focus Malaysia |accessdate=31 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422121504/https://focusmalaysia.my/Assets/rejuvenating-chow-kit|archive-date=22 April 2019}}</ref> Many of the [[prostitute]]s are daughters of prostitutes and have grown up in the area.<ref>{{Cite news | year = 2006 | url = http://thestaronline.com/news/story.asp?file=/2006/7/9/nation/14761340&sec=nation | title = Uncertain future for Chow Kit children | work = thestaronline.com | accessdate = 21 July 2006 | archive-date = 17 February 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120217094823/http://thestaronline.com/news/story.asp?file=%2F2006%2F7%2F9%2Fnation%2F14761340&sec=nation | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Malaysian director Justin Ong's 2013 film, ''Ida's choice'', is about a young woman in the red-light district.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ida's choice |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/witness/2013/03/201332512410892945.html |website=www.aljazeera.com |accessdate=31 January 2019 |date=26 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe [[KL Monorail]] [[Chow Kit Monorail station]] is situated in this area, and the [[Ampang Line]] [[PWTC LRT station]] is located nearby.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Chow Kit Road became the subject of the hit song, ''Chow Kit Road'', made famous by the late [[Sudirman Arshad]].<ref name=\"chowkit\"/> Sudirman held an open-air concert on the road in 1986 to a 100,000-strong audience.<ref name=\"sudirmanconcert\">[http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2013/04/05/good-ol-charm-of-jalan-chow-kit/ Good ol\u2019 charm of Jalan Chow Kit]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:SHOPPING_2_0042.jpg|The wet market\nFile:MURTABAK_1_0031.jpg|Murtabak (pancake) seller\nFile:CHICKEN_1_0050.jpg|Chicken meat in Chow Kit\nFile:ANCHOVY_1_0058.jpg|Small-sized anchovies in Chow Kit\nFile:Bazaar Baru Chow Kit 631.jpg|[[Carambola]] \nFile:Bazaar Baru Chow Kit 632.jpg|[[Pitaya]]\nFile:Bazaar Baru Chow Kit 634.jpg|[[Durian]]\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Chow Kit}}\n\n{{Etnic Enclaves in Malaysia}}\n{{Greater Kuala Lumpur}}\n\n[[Category:African diaspora in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Suburbs in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Indonesian diaspora in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Red-light districts in Malaysia]]\n\n\n{{malaysia-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Thomstho", "label": "safe", "comment": "proofread", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chow_Kit"}
{"title_page": "List of acquisitions by Cisco Systems", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n[[File:Ciscosystemsheadquarters.jpg|thumb|right|The Cisco Systems campus in San Jose]]\n[[Cisco Systems]] is an American [[computer networking]] company. Cisco made its first [[Takeover|acquisition]] in 1993,<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=April 16, 2008|url=http://www.cisco.com/web/about/ac49/ac20/downloads/annualreport/ar2004/pdf/ar_2004_editorial.pdf|title=A Communications Revolution |publisher=[[Cisco Systems]]}}</ref> which was followed by a series of further acquisitions.\n\n==History==\nFounded in 1987, Cisco did not acquire a company during the first seven years of its existence; but, on September 24, 1993, Cisco acquired [[Crescendo Communications]], a [[LAN switching]] company.<ref name=\"crescendo 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/02_03/b3766006.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020116065334/http://businessweek.com/magazine/content/02_03/b3766006.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 16, 2002|title=Cisco Shopped till It Nearly Dropped|publisher=[[BusinessWeek]]|accessdate=April 28, 2008}}</ref> Following the first Cisco takeover purchase, acquisitions have constituted 50 percent of the company's business activity.<ref name=\"crescendo 2\" />\n\nThe company's largest acquisition {{as of|2008|4|lc=on}} is the purchase of [[Scientific-Atlanta]]\u2014a manufacturer of [[cable television]], [[telecommunications]] and [[broadband]] equipment\u2014for [[United States dollar|US$]]6.9 billion. The purchase represented the interest that Cisco had in Internet television, as spending on switches and routers decreased, and expanded the corporation's consumer product base after its prior acquisition of Linksys Inc., a producer of wireless networking products for homes and small businesses. Cisco [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) at the time, John Chambers, described it as a \"medium-sized\" purchase, but the acquisition was the largest since Cisco paid US$7.29 billion for Cerent Corporation in 1999. The deal was announced in November 2005 and was finalized in early 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cisco Agrees to Buy Scientific-Atlanta for $6.9 Bln (Update8)|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=awnLzqzOM2A8&refer=us|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113150619/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=awnLzqzOM2A8&refer=us|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 13, 2015|accessdate=May 24, 2014|newspaper=Bloomberg|date=November 18, 2005|author=Rebecca Barr}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of companies acquired by Cisco are based in the United States (U.S.) and a total of 149 companies have been acquired {{as of|2011|3|lc=on}}.<ref name=\"Acquisitions by Year\">{{cite web |title=Acquisitions by Year |url=https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/about/corporate-strategy-office/acquisitions/acquisitions-list-years.html |website=www.cisco.com |accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> Most of the companies acquired by Cisco are related to computer networking, with several LAN switching and [[Voice over Internet Protocol]] (VoIP) companies included in the list of acquisitions.<ref name=\"Acquisitions by Year\"/>\n\n==Acquisitions==\nEach acquisition is for the respective company in its entirety, unless otherwise specified, and the date of the agreement between Cisco Systems and the subject of the acquisition is listed. The value of each acquisition is listed in the US$ currency because Cisco Systems is headquartered in [[California]], U.S.\n\nMost of the products and business comes through acquisition. Cisco Systems has spent more than 70 billion dollars for acquisition.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Company\n! Business\n! Country\n! Value ([[United States Dollar|USD]])\n!class=\"unsortable\"|References\n|-\n| {{dts|1993|9|24}}\n| [[Crescendo Communications]]\n| [[LAN switching]]\n| {{USA}}\n|align=\"right\"|${{nts|94500000}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/why-cisco-showered-three-men-with-billions-2014-9|title=Why Cisco Has Showered These 3 Men With Billions Of Dollars|newspaper=Business Insider|access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1994|7|12}}\n| [[Newport Systems Solutions]]\n| [[Router (computing)|Router]]\n| {{USA}}\n|align=\"right\"|${{nts|95000000}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=April 15, 2008|url=http://newsroom.cisco.com/dlls/1994/corp_071294.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030803003136/http://newsroom.cisco.com/dlls/1994/corp_071294.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 3, 2003|title=Cisco to Acquire Newport Systems Solutions|publisher=[[Cisco Systems]]|date=July 12, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=April 28, 2008|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/59565001.html?dids=59565001:59565001&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Aug+09%2C+1994&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Newport+Systems+Deal+Completed&pqatl=google|title=Newport Systems Deal Completed |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=August 9, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/q/hp?s=CSCO&a=06&b=12&c=1994&d=06&e=12&f=1994&g=d|title=Cisco Stock Price on July 12, 1994}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1994|10|24}}\n| [[Kalpana (company)|Kalpana]]\n| [[LAN switching]]\n| {{USA}}\n|align=\"right\"|${{nts|204000000}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=April 28, 2008|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9506E7DF153FF936A15753C1A962958260 |title=COMPANY NEWS; Cisco to Buy Major Maker Of Switches |publisher=The New York Times |first=Lawrence M. |last=Fisher |date=October 25, 1994}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1994|12|8}}\n| [[LightStream]]\n| [[Asynchronous Transfer Mode|ATM switching]]\n| {{USA}}\n|align=\"right\"|${{nts|120000000}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=April 11, 2015|url=http://how-to-become-an-entrepren