 | accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Composite Software]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cisco.com/web/about/doing_business/corporate_development/acquisitions/ac_year/about_cisco_acquisition_years_list.html Official website (Acquisitions)]\n\n{{List of mergers and acquisitions by}}\n{{featured list}}\n\n[[Category:Cisco Systems acquisitions| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of corporate acquisitions|Cisco Systems]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n[[File:Ciscosystemsheadquarters.jpg|thumb|right|The Cisco Systems campus in San Jose]]\n[[Cisco Systems]] is an American [[computer networking]] company. Cisco made its first [[Takeover|acquisition]] in 1993,<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=April 16, 2008|url=http://www.cisco.com/web/about/ac49/ac20/downloads/annualreport/ar2004/pdf/ar_2004_editorial.pdf|title=A Communications Revolution |publisher=[[Cisco Systems]]}}</ref> which was followed by a series of further acquisitions.\n\n==History==\nFounded in 1987, Cisco did not acquire a company during the first seven years of its existence; but, on September 24, 1993, Cisco acquired [[Crescendo Communications]], a [[LAN switching]] company.<ref name=\"crescendo 2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/02_03/b3766006.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020116065334/http://businessweek.com/magazine/content/02_03/b3766006.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 16, 2002|title=Cisco Shopped till It Nearly Dropped|publisher=[[BusinessWeek]]|accessdate=April 28, 2008}}</ref> Following the first Cisco takeover purchase, acquisitions have constituted 50 percent of the company's business activity.<ref name=\"crescendo 2\" />\n\nThe company's largest acquisition {{as of|2008|4|lc=on}} is the purchase of [[Scientific-Atlanta]]\u2014a manufacturer of [[cable television]], [[telecommunications]] and [[broadband]] equipment\u2014for [[United States dollar|US$]]6.9 billion. The purchase represented the interest that Cisco had in Internet television, as spending on switches and routers decreased, and expanded the corporation's consumer product base after its prior acquisition of Linksys Inc., a producer of wireless networking products for homes and small businesses. Cisco [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) at the time, John Chambers, described it as a \"medium-sized\" purchase, but the acquisition was the largest since Cisco paid US$7.29 billion for Cerent Corporation in 1999. The deal was announced in November 2005 and was finalized in early 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cisco Agrees to Buy Scientific-Atlanta for $6.9 Bln (Update8)|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=awnLzqzOM2A8&refer=us|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113150619/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=awnLzqzOM2A8&refer=us|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 13, 2015|accessdate=May 24, 2014|newspaper=Bloomberg|date=November 18, 2005|author=Rebecca Barr}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of companies acquired by Cisco are based in the United States (U.S.) and a total of 149 companies have been acquired {{as of|2011|3|lc=on}}.<ref name=\"Acquisitions by Year\">{{cite web |title=Acquisitions by Year |url=https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/about/corporate-strategy-office/acquisitions/acquisitions-list-years.html |website=www.cisco.com |accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> Most of the companies acquired by Cisco are related to computer networking, with several LAN switching and [[Voice over Internet Protocol]] (VoIP) companies included in the list of acquisitions.<ref name=\"Acquisitions by Year\"/>\n\n==Acquisitions==\nEach acquisition is for the respective company in its entirety, unless otherwise specified, and the date of the agreement between Cisco Systems and the subject of the acquisition is listed. The value of each acquisition is listed in the US$ currency because Cisco Systems is headquartered in [[California]], U.S.\n\nMost of the products and business comes through acquisition. Cisco Systems has spent more than 70 billion dollars for acquisition.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Company\n! Business\n! Country\n! Value ([[United States Dollar|USD]])\n!class=\"unsortable\"|References\n|-\n| {{dts|1993|9|24}}\n| [[Crescendo Communications]]\n| [[LAN switching]]\n| {{USA}}\n|align=\"right\"|${{nts|94500000}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/why-cisco-showered-three-men-with-billions-2014-9|title=Why Cisco Has Showered These 3 Men With Billions Of Dollars|newspaper=Business Insider|access-date=January 25, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1994|7|12}}\n| [[Newport Systems Solutions]]\n| [[Router (computing)|Router]]\n| {{USA}}\n|align=\"right\"|${{nts|95000000}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=April 15, 2008|url=http://newsroom.cisco.com/dlls/1994/corp_071294.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030803003136/http://newsroom.cisco.com/dlls/1994/corp_071294.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 3, 2003|title=Cisco to Acquire Newport Systems Solutions|publisher=[[Cisco Systems]]|date=July 12, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=April 28, 2008|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/59565001.html?dids=59565001:59565001&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Aug+09%2C+1994&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Newport+Systems+Deal+Completed&pqatl=google|title=Newport Systems Deal Completed |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=August 9, 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/q/hp?s=CSCO&a=06&b=12&c=1994&d=06&e=12&f=1994&g=d|title=Cisco Stock Price on July 12, 1994}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|1994|10|24}}\n| [[Kalpana (company)|Kalpana]]\n| [[LAN switching]]\n| {{USA}}\n|align=\"right\"|${{nts|204000000}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=April 28, 2008|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9506E7DF153FF936A1